            "@type": "dctypes:Text",
            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><em><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">HT.V-VI.R6</span></em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">The great effect.<br /><br /></span></strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial,sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Given its placement, this note seems to be a general header for this weekly installment comprising chapters 33 and 34, and seems to refer primarily to his handling of Stephen&rsquo;s discovery and death. As this was to be the penultimate installment in the novel&rsquo;s serial run, clearly Dickens was conscious of managing the novel&rsquo;s key narrative elements as it moved toward its conclusion. The focus on Stephen&rsquo;s absence, emphasized at the start and end of chapter 33 (and carried over from the prior installment&ndash;all documented here on the Working Note), is clearly managed with &ldquo;great effect.&rdquo; The same applies as well to Stephen&rsquo;s melodramatic discovery and sentimentalized death-scene in chapter 34. The revelation of &ldquo;Mrs Pegler [as] Bounderby&rsquo;s mother&rdquo; is also a scene of characteristic Dickensian &ldquo;effect,&rdquo; similar to scenes like the exposure of Mr. Pecksniff in <em>Martin Chuzzlewit</em> and the &ldquo;smash[ing]&rdquo; of Uriah Heep in <em>David Copperfield</em> (see DC_WN_17).</span></p>",
            "format": "text/html"
        }
    ],
